==English==

===Noun===
'''gauntlet'''  (''plural:'' '''[[gauntlets]]''')
# (''Armor'') [[Category:Armor]] Protective [[armor]] for the [[hand]]s.
#:'''Quotations'''
#:*'''1786''': The hands were defended by [[Gauntlet]]s, these were sometimes of chain [[mail]], but oftener of small plates of iron [[rivet]]ted together, in imitation of the [[lobster]]'s tail, so as to yield every motion of the hand, some [[gauntlet]]s [[inclose]]d the whole hand, as in a box or case, others were divided into [[finger]]s, each finger consisting of eight or ten separate pieces, the inside [[glove]]d with [[buff]] [[leather]], some of these reached no higher than the [[wrist]], others to the [[elbow]]; the latter were [[stile]]d long armed [[gauntlet]]s: many of them are to be seen in the Tower; for a representation of one of them, see plate 26, fig 6. &mdash; Francis Grose, ''A Treatise on Ancient Armour and Weapons'', page 22.

A gauntlet can also refer to an ordeal that must be completed, generally as atonement or punishment.  Formerly, it refered to the specific act of running between two parallel rows of men, who struck the offender with rods or other weapons as he went through, or it can refer to the rows of people administering this.
It may also mean an attack from two or more sides at the same time, or to any situation that is challenging, difficult, or painful.

